column168: On June 4, 2023, at 1915 hours, personnel in the CSXT Walbridge, OH Yard discovered a strong odor emitting from CPCX 205191, a residue tank car of Combustible Liquid, N.O.S. The car was isolated and the shipper, Lubrizol, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2023-0605-00294).  EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the odor was emitting from a faulty Vacuum Relief Valve (VRV). The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Joe Eskra (440-364-9372, joe.eskra@lubrizol.com).  Contractor personnel removed the faulty VRV and secured the opening with a pipe plug.  The car was held at the CSX Walbridge yard pending a One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from the FRA.

column168: SequenceEvent: The unprocessed box was found wet in the load area and moved to the hazmat cage for reports. DescribePack: Contents were leaking from under the cap on one of the jugs in the box, even though the cap was on tight.   The label on the box had a 96220302 service code on it. The service code in the system is 96220019.  The contents in the box and the OP-909 are different than HESS.  The contents are actually 100% Reagent Alcohol, (Ethanol Solutions, UN1170, II, Flammable Liquid).  Ftrack has no hazmat information listed.  These items were mentioned in the second ISP entered. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was placed upright in a hazbag lined tote.

SequenceEvent: The package arrived already wet to the station and it was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further containment and inspection. DescribePack: All 4 plastic bottles leaked from loose caps. The bottles have a seal but the caps were not secured. No padding or inner packing materials were used. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon arrival the wet package was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further containment. No release was found.

column168: 1.X-2023060560 SequenceEvent: Package handler found package leaking and called to qa for inspection from trailer# 830244 around 6:30 am. Called to QA. QA retrieved package and inspected. Upon inspection, QA determined it was damages and the package was placed in Hazardous materials bin and placed outside due to ventilation. DescribePack: There were loose caps that leads to leakage of the hazardous materials DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: QA determined it was damages and the package was placed in Hazardous materials bin and placed outside due to ventilation.   2. X-2023060567 SequenceEvent: Package handler found the leaking package and called for QA to inspect package coming from trailer 830244 around 6:37. column168: SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN THE QA AREA. THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF DAMAGE IS UNKNOWN. DescribePack: ONE GLASS BOTTLE IS BROKEN DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: ABSORBENT

SequenceEvent: The package was discovered at Mokena Station 610 on the 200 van line between work areas 216 and 236 by Alpimex BC, Andres Galvez, who immediately informed FedEx Ops Manager, Robert Sanner. During this time, it was discovered that two employees, Darrius Cozart and Jeremy Murray, had come in contact with the hazmat. Robert immediately instructed Darrius and Jeremy to rinse hands under water. Robert then placed damaged hazmat in bag + tote and promptly removed the package from the work area. He then communicated incident to ops admins, Emil Wisch (myself) and Keeli Palmateer.     Emil & Keeli instantly moved to location to assess the incident. There was a small amount of the hazmat spilled in drops under the line/rollers between work areas 216 and 236. There were two places where the spill was more concentrated (one was roughly an area of 10" X 2" and the other roughly 14" x 2"). Emil instructed nearby managers, package handlers, BCs and drivers to stay clear of the area and left to retrieve PPE and cleanup materials while Keeli researched first aid response for Darrius and Jeremy. She echoed Robert's instructions of running contact areas under water (adding the details running under COLD water for 15 MINUTES).    Darrius and Jeremy were moved to the office where Senior Manager, Nancy Morris and P&D Manager, Patryk Rojewski took over first aid.    Emil returned and spread AMPHOMAG neutralizer on spill locations while Keeli observed (training).    It was later discovered that the spill had actually originated in a trailer in the unload. It is unknown how the damage to the package occurred. There were no reports of any injuries to any employees who were near that trailer at the time the package was unloaded. Emil and Keeli moved to the location where the spill had originated. Emil spread AMPHOMAG neutralizer on all visible locations of the spilled hazmat while Keeli observed (training).    Emil and Keeli later returned to both locations where the neutralizer was spread and collected all materials in hazmat bags and totes.    There are no known complications to employees, Darrius Cozart or Jeremy Murray, proceeding the incident up to the time of this report. Both reported to work the following day with no known restrictions. DescribePack: There was a large hole/tear in the outer container of the package. Inside the package were 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottles of hazmat. Each bottle was contained in a plastic bag. One of those bottles' caps was unfastened. No damage DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: 1 hour is overestimating. I believe the release was less than 30 minutes (in our facility, station 610). Response was timely and well-coordinated. Mitigation included prompt first-aid to 2 affected employees, near-instant containment of damaged package allowing no future release and neutralization of acid to prevent any further damage to people, package and facility.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XAQ experienced a UN3264 Reaxis S 50 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons of product released to an 8' x 15' area of the trailer floor and to the asphalt lot below due to a pallet puncture. The product was transferred into a new tote. Soda ash and absorbents were utilized to clean the impacted areas along with other impacted freight. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized. All waste was placed into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2.5ft-by-2.5ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that thirty (30) pounds of material was released due to a load shift  during  transit  damaging  one  (1)  poly  pail  causing  the  lid  to  come  off.  First  Call  Environmental personnel  moved all the  poly pails from the pallet to verify only  one (1)  pail was damaged and then swept up the released material. The non-damaged pails were restacked on to two pallets and shipped onto the consignee. The damaged poly pail was placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum along with the  recovered  released  material  and  was  staged  onsite  at  the  terminal  prior  to  the  contractor demobilizing.  The  generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  for  the  ESTES  DGRM  team  to  coordinate disposal.

column168: On June 1, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of nickel sulfate (UN3082) was damaged due to a load shift and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer floor and concrete surface below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES&H services (ESH) to remediate the site. ESH personnel deployed granular absorbents and worked them in using hand tools as well as utilizing degreasing agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product. The crew overpacked the damaged 275-gallon tote into one (1) 330-gallon tote and all nickel sulfate impacted material in five (5) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

On June 1, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN3266 were damaged during a load shift and released approximately five (5) gallons to the trailer interior. R&L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to assess and remediate the site. HES personnel deployed granular absorbents and absorbent pads to the impacted trailer and swept them in using hand tools. All spent absorbents were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon poly drum for disposal.

column168: The 55 gallon drum in temporary storage at Veolia's PA 10-day intransit facility when it suddenly reacted, causing the drum to rupture. All of the contents of the drum release from the drum into secondary containment in the waste storage area.  While there were employees that were nearby when this occurred, there were no injuries and no exposures.  The pH of the liquid was tested and was found to be between 12 and 13.  This was the only drum in the shipment. Veolia contacted a third party emergency response company to clean up the spill and decontaminate the area.
column169: Veolia will verify with Johns Hopkins that they are classifying the hazardous waste properly. In the future, waste shipments from this generator will be shipped with vented bung caps in place. Shipments from this customer should not occur until a 24 hour waiting period has passed after a container has been filled and closed. Drums displaying any signs of pressure build up will be vented prior to transportation.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NRG experienced a UN2924 Calfon AS 300 release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-gallons of product released to a 40' x 1' area of the trailer floor onto the dock due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged drum along with another dented drum of the same material were each placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All cleanup debris including the impacted pallet were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal NNC experienced a release from 5 boxes, each containing (4) 1-gallon poly pails of UN1760 "Sparclean Detergent II". ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-quarts of product released to the pallet. The pallet was wiped down and neutralized. All damaged boxes and jugs of product were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

DescribePack: Outer package is visibly oily, but box itself is structurally sound with no punctures, crushing, holes, etc. Failure was caused by inadequate packing within the box. Heavy items were able to press and move against fragile items, depressing aerosol can nozzle and allowing spray to leak into box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Box was removed from van line upon discovery. While the outer package is visibly oily, it was not actively leaking. Box damage was noticed quickly, and box was able to be placed into a hazmat bucket. Oily spots on van line were blotted with absorbent disposable cloth towels.

column168: Upon dismantling of PMC17139SQ from SQ7988 - 28Jun2023, Cargo Warehouse   Supervisor Mr. Oscar Castillo sighted that some of skids that belong to MAWB #   618-64200463 were showing signs of slight damage and plastic torn. He chose   to raise a discrepancy and file a report due to crushed skids and ripped plastic.   When opening the cargo to take photos of the inner boxes to look for damages and   pilferage, he discovered the cargo contains undeclared DG for UN3480 in a large quantity.   A report was subsequently sent to HQ, consignee informed via email that the said cargo is on HOLD pending further advise from SQ head office, as well as potential reporting of this   incident to the local authorities. Nobody has been hurt and currently we have the cargo   stored in our DG area. Shipment only arrived with a copy of the MAWB, no other documents were attached. Attempts to contact consignee has been made and no answer to phone / emails.   Per MAWB the said shipment contains 8 skids (palletized) and said to contain 187 ctns   Per MAWB they are declaring the goods to be Intercom Speaker (Non-DG) Per MAWB they also declaring these are LiBat in compliance with section II. (PI967).

On June 6th, a package was discovered during the AM sort that was wet and smelled of fuel.  The outer package had some obscured markings on the outside that, after opening the package and examining the contents, do not appear to be connected with the shipment.  The package contained 3 small receptacles that contained 100mL each of diesel fuel samples.  One of the receptacles  opened causing the entire contents to leak out to be absorbed by the box.  The other 2 receptacles also appear to have cracks in them.  DG Admin advised the station to hold the shipment as it appears to be undeclared since there are no markings on the outside of the package that relates to the diesel fuel inside.

column168: Yard crew reported liquid and a strong odor coming from CTCX 733390.  Upon inspection of the car from the ground, the combination housing could be seen resting on the handle of the liquid line valve.  The valve was in the open position.  On top of the car we found the liquid line plug to be out of the valve body and confirmed the valve was in the open position.  The valve was closed and the plug was installed and secured, stopping the release.  The rest of the fittings on the car were also checked and found to be tight with no releases.
